, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33944" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole psammophila Creighton &amp; Gregg" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole psammophila Creighton &amp; Gregg" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="psammophila">psammophila</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:189143" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole vinelandica Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole vinelandica Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vinelandica">vinelandica</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34107" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole xerophila Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole xerophila Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xerophila">xerophila</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34109" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole yaqui Creighton &amp; Gregg" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole yaqui Creighton &amp; Gregg" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yaqui">yaqui</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181978" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole yucatana Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole yucatana Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yucatana">yucatana</taxonomicName>
, which complex is characterized by the large to very large, forward-set eyes, especially in the minor; and in the major, the occipital lobes lacking any sculpturing (except in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181969" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole aurea Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole aurea Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">aurea</taxonomicName>
); the posterior half of the head capsule almost entirely smooth and shiny; and the postpetiolar node seen from above oval, elliptical, or laterally angulate (cornulate in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33658" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole cerebrosior Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole cerebrosior Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerebrosior">cerebrosior</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33659" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">P. ceres</taxonomicName>
is distinguished within the complex by the following combination of traits. Dark to blackish brown. Major: carinulae originating on the frontal triangle travel along the midline to the occiput; transverse carinulae present along the anterior lateral margins of the pronotum; mesonotal convexity and propodeal spines well-developed; postpetiole from above laterally angulate and diamond-shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="570">Minor: eyes moderately large; mesonotal convexity low but well-developed. Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.14, HL 1.18, SL 0.66, EL 0.16, PW 0.54. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.54, HL 0.60, SL 0.54, EL 0.12, PW 0.34.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="570">Color Major: body blackish brown, with brownish yellow clypeus; appendages brownish yellow to medium brown. Minor: like the major, except that the clypeus is not yellow but dark brown and hence not contrasting.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="570">
Range Foothills of the Rockies in eastern Colorado at 1800-2600 m, southwest to the mountains of New Mexico and Arizona, at 2200-2700 m, as well as extreme eastern Nevada. Also recorded from the Davis Mts. of Texas but evidently rare there (Creighton 1950a: 174), and from Guerrereo Mills, in the mountains of Hidalgo (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151235" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres tepaneca Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres tepaneca Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tepaneca">tepaneca</taxonomicName>
types).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="571" pageNumber="570">
biology According to Stefan Cover, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33659" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">ceres</taxonomicName>
is found at higher elevations and in colder climates than any other 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
species in the western North American fauna. In southern Arizona it is often the only 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
occurring above 2250 m. Gregg (1963) reports
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33659" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">ceres</taxonomicName>
to be the most abundant 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
in Colorado, where it occurs in a wide array of habitats, including ponderosa pine forest, foothills meadowland, and sagebrush. Cover found the species in the same general habitats in Arizona and New Mexico. In Nevada G. C. and J. Wheeler (1986g) found a colony at 2650 m in juniper-pinyon woodland. The ants collect and store seeds of a variety of grasses and herbaceous angiosperms. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33659" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">P. ceres</taxonomicName>
nests in several types of open soil under rocks. Colonies are large and active, consisting of up to 1000 ants. Majors are numerous and most colonies are monogynous. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33659" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ceres Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">P. ceres</taxonomicName>
is also notable as the host of the workerles parasite 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33721" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole elecebra (Wheeler)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole elecebra (Wheeler)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elecebra">P. elecebra</taxonomicName>
. Winged sexuals have been found in nests principally from early to the middle of July, with one record of males on 9 September. Winged reproductives have been found in nests throughout July, and a wingless queen was collected on 21 July, presumably following a nuptial flight.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
